{
  "doc_id": "56945",
  "text": "The frequent failures of targeted therapy recently brought renewed attention to intra-tumor heterogeneity. A drug designed to target the particular oncogene driving a tumor was expected to provide a magic bullet that would kill all the cancer cells depending on it. [CITATION_1] Although dramatic initial responses to such drugs could be obtained, these were almost always followed by relapse and tumor regrowth. [CITATION_2] Intra-tumor heterogeneity, as proposed decades previously, provided a reasonable explanation for such initial success followed by treatment failure: therapy selecting for pre-existing subclones that had mutated in ways that happened to provide resistance.",
